      <item>
        <title>Close GitHub Issue With Commit Message</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Did you know you can close a GitHub issue with a commit message?  I didn&#39;t know that either, until recently.  It&#39;s turned out to be a pretty handy feature.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-vim&quot; data-lang=&quot;vim&quot;&gt;git commit &lt;span class=&quot;p&quot;&gt;-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;k&quot;&gt;m&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;s1&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;closes #13&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p&gt;You don&#39;t have to be closing an issue to mention it in a commit.  There are several keywords you can use to reference issues; &lt;code&gt;started&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;continued&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;closes&lt;/code&gt; are the main keywords.  You can view the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/blog/1386-closing-issues-via-commit-messages&quot;&gt;GitHub Blog&lt;/a&gt; for a little more information on the issue.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I tend to create an issue for everything I want to change with my site, so I tend to have a lot of open issues.  Being able to close issues witha commit message makes it super easy to keep track of what I&#39;ve done work on, what I&#39;m working on, and what I&#39;ve finished working on.&lt;/p&gt;

